## Introduction

The Tourism Webpage is designed to provide information about various tourist destinations. It includes an appealing layout with responsive design elements to ensure it looks great on both desktop and mobile devices.

## Features

- **Responsive Design**: Ensures the webpage looks good on all devices.
- **Semantic HTML**: Uses semantic HTML elements for better accessibility and SEO.
- **Custom CSS**: Includes a CSS file to style the HTML content.

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites

To view and edit this project, you will need a modern web browser and a text editor. We recommend:

- [Google Chrome](https://www.google.com/chrome/) or [Mozilla Firefox](https://www.mozilla.org/firefox/)
- [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/) or [Sublime Text](https://www.sublimetext.com/)

### Installation

To get a copy of the project up and running on your local machine, follow these simple steps:

1. **Clone the repository**:
    ```sh
    git clone <repository_url>
    ```

2. **Navigate to the project directory**:
    ```sh
    cd tourism-webpage
    ```

## Usage

To use the Tourism Webpage, open the `Tourism_webpage.html` file in your preferred web browser. You can do this by double-clicking the file or by right-clicking it and selecting "Open with" and choosing your browser.

## Project Structure

The project directory contains the following files:

tourism-webpage/
│
├── Tourism_webpage.html # Main HTML file
├── Tourism_webpage.css # CSS file for styling
└── README.md # Project documentation


### Detailed Description of Files

- **Tourism_webpage.html**: Contains the HTML structure of the webpage, including various sections like header, main content, and footer.
- **Tourism_webpage.css**: Contains CSS rules to style the HTML content. This includes layout, typography, colors, and responsive design adjustments.

